---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../consts';
import { topics, topicsByCategory, allPosts } from '../lib/content';
const posts = await allPosts();
const grouped = topicsByCategory();

const aboutUrl = new URL('/about', Astro.site).toString();
const description = `About Penluma: ${posts.length} in-depth, worked-through notes on system design, distributed systems, economics, money, and clear thinking - from intuition to mechanics to failure modes.`;

const keywords = [
  'Penluma',
  'about',
  'deep-dive notes',
  'system design',
  'distributed systems',
  'economics',
  'clear thinking',
  'money',
];

const jsonLd = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'AboutPage',
    name: `About ${SITE.name}`,
    description,
    url: aboutUrl,
    mainEntity: {
      '@type': 'Person',
      name: SITE.author,
      url: new URL('/', Astro.site).toString(),
    },
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: new URL('/', Astro.site).toString() },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'About', item: aboutUrl },
    ],
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description={description} keywords={keywords} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-white">About Penluma</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300">
      A growing library of {posts.length} deep-dives that take hard topics from first intuition all
      the way to how they break in production.
    </p>
    <div class="prose-research mt-8">
      <p>
        <strong>Penluma</strong> - <em>pen</em> + <em>lumen</em>, the light of the pen - is a growing
        library of <strong>{posts.length} deep-dive notes</strong> across
        <strong>{topics.length} topics</strong>, from staff-level system design and distributed
        systems to economics, clear thinking, and money. Every topic is written to take you from
        plain-language intuition, to precise mechanics, to the failure modes that show up in the
        real world.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike most online write-ups, these aren't cheat sheets. They include back-of-the-envelope
        math, worked examples, comparison tables, war stories, and test-yourself questions. They're
        meant to be read slowly and worked through - the version I wish I'd had when I was learning
        each of these things.
      </p>

      <h2>The problem I'm trying to solve</h2>
      <p>
        Most explanations sit at one of two extremes. Cheat sheets and hot takes are easy to read
        but too shallow to use - you finish them <em>knowing about</em> a topic without actually
        understanding it. Textbooks and papers are rigorous but so dense that most people bounce off
        before the idea ever clicks. Both leave you stranded the moment you hit a real problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        Penluma aims for the missing middle: writing that is genuinely deep but still readable -
        rigorous where it counts, plain-language where it can be.
      </p>

      <h2>The method: every topic, three levels deep</h2>
      <p>Each deep-dive is built to move through three layers, in order:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Intuition</strong> - the plain-language mental model first, the way a smart friend
          would explain it before any jargon shows up.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Mechanics</strong> - precisely how the thing actually works, step by step. No
          hand-waving, no "it just works."
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Failure modes</strong> - where it breaks in the real world, why, and what to do
          about it. This is the part most explanations skip, and it's usually the part that matters.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What you'll find here</h2>
      <p>
        The library spans {topics.length} topics grouped into a handful of areas. It keeps growing
        as I work through new material:
      </p>
      <ul>
        {grouped.map((g) => (
          <li><strong>{g.category}</strong> - {g.topics.length} {g.topics.length === 1 ? 'topic' : 'topics'}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <h2>Who this is for</h2>
      <p>
        Penluma is for the curious builder, operator, or student who would rather understand
        something properly than skim ten summaries of it - engineers levelling up toward staff,
        founders trying to reason about their own business, and anyone who likes chasing an idea all
        the way to the bottom. If you want a quick answer to copy-paste, this probably isn't the
        place. If you want to actually <em>get</em> it, welcome.
      </p>

      <h2>How to get the most out of it</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Read slowly. These are worked through, not skimmed - treat them like a short chapter, not a tweet.</li>
        <li>Do the math and the test-yourself questions instead of nodding past them; that's where understanding actually sticks.</li>
        <li>Follow a numbered series start to finish - the ordering is deliberate, each part builds on the last.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who writes this</h2>
      <p>
        I'm {SITE.author} - an engineer and a compulsive learner. Penluma is my habit of taking one
        hard topic at a time and writing through it until the fog clears, then publishing the part
        that survived. There's no team and no ghostwriters: one voice, working things out in the
        open, so the next person learning the same thing gets there faster.
      </p>

      <h2>What makes it different</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Depth over volume</strong> - one topic fully worked through beats ten skimmed for the algorithm.</li>
        <li><strong>Evergreen, not news</strong> - the residue that stays true in five years, not a take that expires next week.</li>
        <li><strong>Open by default</strong> - the whole library is free. No paywall, no signup wall to read.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Stay in the loop</h2>
      <p>
        New deep-dives get added over time. If you'd like to know when a substantial new topic or
        post lands, subscribe using the form at the bottom of the page - one email when there's
        something worth reading, and nothing else.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
